 1. Introduction 
 In Bangladesh, as in many other countries of the 
 developing world, the role of (related to sending and receiving phone calls, texts, etc.) 
 in money-based development does not seem to be duly 
 appreciated. The telecom part/area has received very little 
 attention from policy makers, and the country has seen slow (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) of its network over the years. 
 The country's present (set of machines) is carefully thought about/believed 
 to be not enough in range, technology and the quality of services. A report produced both/together by World 
 Bank and Bangladesh Center for Advanced Studies 
 (BCAS) presented the limits of telecom services in Bangladesh (World Bank and BCAS, 1998, 
 pp. 55): 
 
 0169-5150/011$- see front matterÂ© 2001 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved. 
 PII: S0169-5150(01)00083-4 
 
 262 
 
 A. Bayes/Agricultural Money flow 25 (2001) 261-272 
 
 - the telephone density of 0.39 lines per 100 people 
 is one of the world's lowest (India: 1.0, Nepal: 0.5, 
 Pakistan: 2.1, Sri Skinnya: 1.0, Thailand: 2.5); 
 - the waiting time for a connection is more than 10 
 years and the installation charge of US$_$ 450 for a 
 new line is one of the highest in the world (e.g. 
 Pakistan US$_$ 90, India US$_$ 60); 
 - the charge for calling the UK, US$_$ 1.50/min, is 
 about six times higher than the charge for calling 
 Bangladesh from the UK; 
 - on average, only 2 of 10 calls are successfully completed; the complaint rate averages 50 complaints 
 per 100 lines per year, clearly pointing to/showing the poor 
 quality of services. 
 By and large, the present underdevelopment and 
 poorness of Bangladesh - a country with a per person 
 income of US$_$ 300 and half of its population living below the poorness line - is related to the underdevelopment of basic (set of machines), both physical and human. 
 Almost all areas away from cities remain mostly (unable to be used or understood) and are as a result unable to take advantage 
 of opportunities good for growth and development 
 by, for example, the diffusion of modern technology, 
 extension services, and fast and effective measures 
 for dealing with disasters such as floods. A number 
 of studies have decided on a (proof that one thing definitely causes another) link between lacking (set of machines) and the slow rate of development 
 in areas away from the cities of Bangladesh (e.g. Ahmed and Horseain, 
 1984, pp.l21; Kessides, 1993, pp. 14-23). 
 Given this sad situation, the Grameen Bank 
 (GB) of Bangladesh stepped into providing some solutions. The GB introduced cellular mobile phones 
 in some areas away from cities - (what people commonly call a/not really a) village pay phones 
 (VPPs) -to be operated under its micro-credit programs. The GB entered into the (away from cities) telecom part/area 
 based on the following basic reasons. First, unevenness in the world of information is one of the principal causes of (state where two things are not the same), backwardness and poorness. 
 The lack of access to information is a powerful factor 
 tending to cause to continue poorness in areas away from cities. Second, 
 telephone services can have a visible influence on 
 production, marketing and other important money-based 
 decisions arguing with (away from cities) families. Third, technology (by itself/in and of itself)  cannot be the solution to the problems of 
 (away from cities) development and poorness reduction unless the issue of 'who controls the technology' can be settled. 
 Fourth, even if particular people are unable to buy 
 
 a phone, they should have access to phone service as 
 and when they need it. 
 The following are the goals of this paper: 
 - To learn how and to what extent VPPs can 
 (help increase/show in a good way) the (related to how much money and power people have) uplift of villagers, especially of the poor, by affecting (related to how much money and power people have) 
 limits/guidelines which hold back families. 
 - To test the money-based effects of cellular mobile 
 phones at the household and village levels: at the 
 household level, by guessing the net increase in 
 income came/coming from selling phone services and 
 deciding/figuring out how this increase affects household 
 poorness and food consumption; at village levels, by 
 guessing the personal extra (CS), marketing 
 margins, changes in working well levels (based on 
 case studies). 
 - To test particular social hits/effects. These include 
 changes in the social balance, permission of 
 the (not having money or education), relationship networks and the law 
 and order situation in the villages. 
 - To make suggestions (related to/looking at/thinking about) the design and 
 creation of public policies which are meant 
 to secure/make sure of wider and better access to telecom 
 services among the poor. 
 The paper is organised as follows: Section 2 outlines 
 the data sources employed. Basic information on (away from cities) 
 phone users are given in Section 3, while the effects 
 of phones are discussed in Section 4. Finally, policy 
 ends/end results are drawn in Section 5. 
 
 2. Research approach and data sources 
 To decide/figure out how VPPs affect (away from cities) development 
 and poorness reduction, both owners (sellers of services) and users (buyers of services) were surveyed. 
 The sample of phone owners consisted of 50 people in 50 different villages located at distances of 
 40-50 km from city-based Dhaka. This sample 
 made up/was equal to about 60% of all VPP owners at the time 
 of the survey. 1 The owners were selected at random 
 from a list given by the GB Head Office, Dhaka. 
 The sample of users of VPP services consisted of 400 
 people. This sample was drawn at random from 
 1 By early 2001, 700-800 village pay phones were operating in 
 Bangladesh. 
 
 A. Bayes/ Farming-based Money flow 25 (2001) 261-272 
 
 lists given by the phone owners, and accounts 
 for 27% of all VPP users in the villages (leaving out/keeping out 
 owner-users). 
 This study uses both first (or most important) and secondary data. 
 The first (or most important) data were collected through a field survey 
 done in the months of June through August 1998. 
 Structured lists of questions were given at both 
 the household and village levels. Focus-group discussions were held, and GB branch managers and local 
 people were requested to provide added/more input (related to/looking at/thinking about) their impressions of the (possible greatness or power) and actual 
 effects of VPPs. What's more, case studies of these effects were developed, which needed/demanded intensive analysis. For its secondary data, the study depends on different 
 published and unpublished documents from the government of Bangladesh and GB. 
 
