 The VPP owners earn an average net (money made/good thing received) of 277 Tk. 
 per week. The profit level ranges from as high as 683 
 Tk. per week to as low as -35 Tk. per week. The 
 (money made/good things received) building up from phone services make up/be equal to from 
 about one-fifth to one-fourth of the total income of the 
 sample families. Half of the sample owners collect  a 
 net (money made/good thing received) of &amp;gt;300 Tk. per week, and one-tenth earn 
 &amp;gt;500 Tk. per week. However, the net (money made/good things received) of 16% 
 of the sample phone owners fell &amp;lt; 100 Tk. per week. 
 
 4.1.2. Other choice means of communication 
 People who responded were also asked the following question: "how would you make happy the need for current calls 
 had there been no VPP in your village?" the responses 
 made by three different income groups are presented 
 in Table 7. The most often talked about/said other choice 
 is that one would either go, or hire a person to go 
 to the place concerned. The range of options across 
 income groups is worth talking about/saying. Among the very poor group, 68% would have needed/demanded physical ability to move around (involving time and transport). In the 
 moderately poor and non-poor groups, the similar figures were 56 and 47%, (match up each pair of items in order). In other 
 words, if no VPPs had been available, the poor would 
 have needed/demanded greater added/more physical ability to move around than 
 the non-poor. Just the opposite, however, is the case 
 when other sources of telephone service are used. The 
 non-poor would have used (compared to other things) more of that service than the poor. By and large, it seems that the 
 
