 4.1.3. Personal extra 
 An guess of the CS cooperated with/produced/gave up by VPPs is presented 
 in Table 8. The CS is defined as the difference between the price people actually pay and the price 
 they would be willing to pay for a particular communication. For the purposes of the present study, CS is 
 defined as the price users would have paid for an different mode of communication, minus the price they 
 actually paid for the phone service. So, the extra 
 guessed could also be thought about/believed as the consumer's 
 real income benefits arising out of being able to make 
 a phone call. The calculation of the CS is based on the 
 following ideas (you think are true): 
 - Time and road-transport costs are included for the 
 (possible or/possible greatness or power or)  possible other choice means of communication. For example, we asked the people who responded how 
 much they would have to pay in time and transport 
 
 costs if their only communication other choice was 
 road transport. 
 - The opportunity costs of the time spent were calculated on the basis of winning/most common (away from cities) wage rates. 
 A uniform wage rate was used for both the poor 
 and the non-poor groups as the non-poor group may 
 have the choice of employing wage labour to get information at the poor group's wage rate, 
 rather than at their own higher reservation wage. 
 - The actual cost to phone users amounted to the price 
 they paid at the time of receiving the services. 
 From the data in Table 8, it can be seen that the 
 availability of VPPs provides average users in all income layers  with a fair amount of CS. For example, 
 while the cost of alternate communication is 71.58 
 Tk., using VPP's costs only 16.82 Tk., producing/giving up a extra of 54.77 Tk. per call or 165 Tk. per user per week 
 (assuming three phone calls a week). This compares 
 with household income of 1500 Tk. per week. In 
 other words, the extra so created amounted to 11% 
 of the household income of families with telephone 
 users. The most important (instance of watching, noticing, or making a statement) to be made in 
 Table 8 is, however, that the CS of the poor, at 77.86 
 Tk., is 50% higher than that of the non-poor. This 
 amount of CS, if converted now (away from cities) prices, 
 could buy 12 kg of rough rice. What's more, the 
 moderately poor gain a CS of 91.64 Tk., followed 
 by the very poor (61.30 Tk.). The non-poor 
 (50.78 Tk.) extract the lowest amount of CS. That 
 the poor would collect  the maximum CS following the 
 coming of VPPs is seen/obvious. The poor usually do not 
 have much in the way of other choices to communicate with the outside world, neither relatives to help 
 with a phone call, nor relatives to provide a ride to 
 the destination. For the poor, the coming of VPPs 
 
