 4.1.4. Prices ofproducts and input supplies 
 One of the important effects of VPPs may be 
 that they help avoid sharp swings in demand, supply 
 and the prices of valuable things. The supporters of 
 VPPs guesse that the spreading around of market 
 information to remote villages would help raise farm 
 output prices and lower farm input prices through 
 the method of information diffusion. (in a true way), 
 differences that could be seen (either evening-out prices or smoothing supply) might be attributable 
 not only to telephones, but to a variety of other 
 factors such as roads, (TV, the Internet, etc.), etc. The related 
 'perceptions' of the local people (related to/looking at/thinking about) the utility 
 of the services were thought about/believed to be of value for this 
 research. (in almost the same way), attempts were made to decide/figure out 
 what views were held in control villages. A summary of the money-based and non-money-based benefits, as 
 perceived by the villagers, is presented in Table 9. 
 The average prices of farming-based valuable things (especially of paddy and eggs) were higher in target villages (with phones) than in control villages (without 
 phones). 
 
 For example, farmers in the target villages received 
 70-75% of the paddy prices paid by final people, 
 instead of 65-70% in control villages. The argument that market (wasting very little while working or producing something) is improved is highlighted 
 by one example in particular: the price of eggs in target villages was reported to be 13 Tk. per bali during the period of the survey, compared to 12 Tk. per 
 bali in control villages. Also, vegetable growers 
 in a target village informed us that VPPs helped them 
 by providing them with easy and instant access to the 
 winning/most common what people want to buy and supply situation and, 
 this way, helped them in making appropriate production decisions. Besides, they argued, VPPs have reduced the 
 role of (people or businesses who buy goods to sell to stores, not you) who often used to lie to/fool them in 
 the (not being there; not being present) of market information. 
 The supply of farming-based inputs such as diesel and 
 fertiliser is reported to be smoother and more stable 
 in target villages than in control villages. According 
 to dealers who do business with these inputs, VPPs 
 have made it possible to develop an impression of the 
 supply situation throughout the year, making it possible to guard against unforeseen (events that are dependent on other things that might or might not happen). On 
 the other hand, the lack of such communication facilities in control villages has been reported to (help increase/show in a good way) occasional shortages and price hikes, adding to 
 
