 4.2.1. Dealing with disasters 
 One major benefit of VPPs was seen in JulySeptember 1998, when Bangladesh was hit by the 
 worst flood in modern history and two-thirds of the 
 country's area remained put underwater for &amp;gt;2 months. 
 People and transport began to get stuck on the way. 
 When people got stuck in or near target villages, 
 mobile phones proved to be very valuable for sending 
 messages to worried relatives or informing employers 
 or calling relief (services businesses/government units). During field visits that took 
 place after the floodwater moved back, it was learned 
 that bills for VPPs rose during the flood months to 
 (in a big way) higher averages than in earlier months 
 due to the increased demand for phone services. GB 
 (people in charge) confirmed this things. On the other 
 hand, local government (people in charge) informed us that the 
 availability of VPPs enabled them to take stock of the 
 situation quickly during the flood. 
 4.3. Socio-cultural effects 
 4.3.1. Law and order situation 
 In a few of the sample villages, it was reported that 
 the law and order situation had improved as a result of 
 the availability of VPPs. In the event of any crime (of stealing) 
 or theft, villagers in target villages were able to inform law-enforcement (services businesses/government units) quickly by phone. In 
 addition, police (services businesses/government units) in the area also 
 reported that fast communication with target villages 
 added/gave to decreasing crimes rates. 
 4.3.2. Across the ocean communication 
 In almost all villages, a fairly large number of people are reported to be working in other countries. Many of them 
 belong to poor families who sold land and other valuable things to pay for their travel. The residents of target 
 villages informed us that communication with the outside world had become very fast and regular following 
 the (the act of reaching a destination) of VPPs in villages. 
 
 A. Bayes/ Farming-based Money flow 25 (2001) 261-272 
 
 4.3.3. Health 
 It was pointed out earlier that roughly one-tenth of 
 all calls deal with health-related matters, especially 
 among poor people. As a result of the availability of 
 VPPs, villagers can now contact clinics, doctors or emergency vehicles quickly, even at night. This was not possible 
 in the past. During discussions with focus groups and 
 interactions with the local elite and social workers, it 
 was showed that the greatest benefit brought about 
 by VPPs was the ability to call doctors and clinics 
 quickly. In a country where the infant death rate is 
 91 per 1000 live births and the mother-based death rate 
 is also very high, VPPs' (thing that's given/work that's done) to saving lives 
 can hardly be (made to appear much bigger, worse, etc., than it really is). 
 4.3.4. Permission of women 
 Different studies in the big picture  of micro-credit programs in Bangladesh argue that there have been 
 big positive developments in the permission of women (e.g. Amin et al., 1998, pp. 36). 
 Findings (related to/looking at/thinking about) permission are presented in 
 Table 11. It may be watched/followed that sample families' 
 decision-making processes are ruled by joint 
 decisions made by both the husband and the wife. 
 That is, whenever household-level decisions have to 
 be made relating to/connected to family affairs, the use of 
 GB credit, or the spending of phone income, both 
 members of the pair participate. For example, 72% of 
 the people who responded replied that the decisions on family 
 affairs (e.g. education for children, the marriage of 
 daughters or sons, etc.) are made by both partners 
 on the basis of back and forth/equal between people discussion. The percentage 
 is 60% when the use of GB credit is at issue. 
 When the issue involved is the spending of earnings 
 from telephone services, however, 58% of the owners 
 make combined decisions, while 36% decide completely on 
 their own. In other words, sample women appear to 
 have greater (north-south position/freedom) in deciding how to spend phone 
 
 269 
 
 income than is the case when the other two issues are 
 involved. For example, 36% of the people who responded decide 
 completely on their own where and how to spend phone 
 (money made/good things received), compared to 16 and 30% for the other two 
 cases, (match up each pair of items in order). Chi-square test results point to/show 
 that these differences are (meaningful numbers). 
 Another indicator of permission is the degree of 
 ability to move around of women in and around the village. Usually/(in the past), Bangladeshi women are 'locked in' the house 
 and rarely have the right to move freely around the 
 village. Of course, the role of GB and other NGOs has 
 broken this chain a little bit by giving women 
 opportunities to come out of the household and become involved in income-creating activities. However, most of those activities have been kept to/restricted to  the 
 reasons where they live (kitchen gardening, (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) 
 rearing, sewing, etc.). Ownership of a mobile phone 
 seems to have opened a new dimension in this respect. The team of (people who work to find information) was able to watch/notice 
 that the mobile phones gave their owners greater ability to move around within the village than they had before. This is 
 because incoming calls for villagers make it necessary 
 to take the phone to them, and if no family members 
 are found to be available, the women themselves have 
 to rush about with the mobile phone. This job they 
 have to perform even during the night. Since many of 
 the phones are placed in their shops in a nearby hat 
 or shop-related (small market), owners were found to go 
 to the phone whenever needed. So, mobile phones 
 appear to have improved women's ability to move around not only 
 within the village, but also outside it. 
 Two added/more parts of the ability to move around issue should 
 be talked about/said. First, women in the village come to 
 the owner's house to make phone calls, and second, 
 sample women reported that the mobile phones expanded the extent of/the range of their ability to move around even beyond the 
 local markets. For example, whenever they decided to 
 visit relatives far away from their villages, they could 
 
