 4.3.5. Changes in social balance and status 
 Many phone-owning families did not appear to 
 be poor families at the time of the survey. On 
 the opposite, they appeared to be (compared to other things) well-off 
 within the big picture  of their money-based conditions: moderately furnished houses, some TV sets, sanitary latrines, tube-wells, etc. Between 5 and 10 years ago, 
 however, many of these families were below the 
 poorness line, and GB micro-credit programs helped 
 them to slowly escape from grinding poorness. However, for their money-based uplift, the women had to depend on the help of some their village's rich 
 elite. Now, however, they are reported to be standing on their own feet. Interestingly, some of the people who came to their reasons to make phone calls 
 were the (compared to other things) rich villagers who had earlier helped them with food, clothing and shelter. Reportedly, customer/financial supporter-client relationships grew up between 
 some of them. For example, about one-fourth of the 
 phone owners reported that the people who depend 
 on them for phone calls include some people who 
 once lent them money to help them overcome money problemss. (in almost the same way), 12% of the phone owners reported that some phone users had once hired 
 them as servants. And 34% reported that they 
 were helped in different ways by many of the users 
 (Table 12). 
 The women in control of cellular mobile phones are 
 proud of their present business. According to them, 
 it has not only helped them earn added/more income, 
 but ownership has also gave to them a certain 
 amount of fame. Everyone in their village and in (next to) villages now knows them and identifies their 
 
