 was not the case when the same women used to begin/try traditional activities such as (related to chickens, hens, turkeys, etc.) rearing, rice 
 husking or grocery selling. Their social status is further improved by the increased income that seems to be 
 raising their household's standard of living. Villagers 
 now respect phone owners. Some of them are also invited to social functions (even to marriage (formal, special events or series of actions) 
 of the village's elite), something which would have 
 been (too terrible to think about) in the big picture  of (away from cities) Bangladesh 
 earlier. 
 4.3.6. Knowledge and confidence 
 Discussions with phone owners point to/show that phone 
 ownership provides not only weekly income, but also 
 knowledge about many things which used to be almost unknown to sample women. For example, when 
 business people approach them to make phone calls 
 to different markets, the women, who stand beside the caller, get to know the names of the markets and the 
 valuable things in which they generally deal. When villagers receive calls from outside the country, the phone 
 owners get to know the names of the places from 
 which the calls start. Sometimes owners are told 
 about the currency or the (related to how much money and power people have) conditions 
 in that particular country. So, each day, owners get 
 to know new things and expand the edge of something/unexplored area of their 
 knowledge. Mobile phone ownership has given these 
 women confidence. The fact that they are collecting the 
 rewards of their good records of repayment and the 
 fulfilment of other judging requirements needed/demanded by GB adds/gives 
 to this confidence. Once they assumed that they would 
 have to sell eggs, puffed rice or cow milk throughout their lives in order to make out a living. They could 
 hardly have dreamed that they would now own a modern 
 communication technology such as a cellular mobile 
 phone. 
 4.3. 7. Strengthening relationship networks 
 Another important effect of VPPs can be seen in 
 the strengthening of relationship networks. The coming of 
 VPPs has enabled villagers to stay in touch with relatives living outside the village. In typical Bangladeshi 
 (community of people/all good people in the world), collecting news about immediate family members and other relations in far places is a repeating 
 concern. In the past, it was not possible to main- 
 
 A. Bayes I Farming-based Money flow 25 (2001) 261-272 
 
 tain a level of relationship interaction just like that 
 which VPPs now allow at such low transaction costs. 
 Without VPPs, efforts to maintain relationship 
 networks were not only expensive, but also (compared to other things) 
 ineffective. 
 
 5. Ends/end results and policy effects/results/suggestions 
 The availability of village pay phones results in 
 big (related to how people and cultures interact) benefits in areas away from cities. For 
 example, the ownership of the phones by (compared to other things) 
 poor families tends to raise their social status and 
 pave the way for change in the social balance. 
 Mobile phones make women more mobile both within 
 and outside their villages. Also, increased 
 income from phones also raises their exchange (government money) in the market and, this way, helps to reduce 
 their poorness. Villages with phones also report that 
 they are very useful in dealing with natural bad events and improving law-enforcement. Given these 
 multi-dimensional benefits of village phones, the study 
 arrives at the following general ends/end results and policy 
 effects/results/suggestions. 
 5.1. Parting with old perceptions 
 Telephones should be treated not only as a person good, but also as a production good, especially 
 in poor areas away from cities. There, telephones are not a domain reserved for (compared to other things) rich, as has been 
 thought by some, but a market in which lower income 
 groups also have big stakes once they gain 
 access. These findings call for a fast re-orientation 
 in the thinking of policy-makers. The development of 
 telecom services in areas away from cities appears to be a factor 
 powerfully (helping increase/showing in a good way) and supporting the goals 
 of (away from cities) development and poorness reduction. Further 
 research on the role of communications technology 
 is needed to increase our understanding of these 
 links. 
 5.2. (removal of controlling laws) and opportunities for 
 the (people and businesses that are not part of the government) 
 
 271 
 
 of VPPs in Bangladesh is a (something produced along with something else) of policies 
 designed to bring about gradual (removal of controlling laws), liberalisation and (turning things over from the government to private companies), which the government has 
 been chasing after in the telecom part/area for some 
 years. Progress in this direction should be fast. Allowing the (people and businesses that are not part of the government) to play a competitive 
 role in the telecom business would reduce the cost of 
 calls and increase the (wasting very little while working or producing something) of the system. The 
 BTTB should be prepared to accept the presence and 
 activities of the (people and businesses that are not part of the government). The government can 
 keep/hold ownership of fixed lines while (giving power, property, or rights) the (people and businesses that are not part of the government) with cellular phones. Investment must be 
 stimulated in the part/area. Quite obviously, ability (to hold or do something) is 
 seriously limited. A public-private partnership may 
 be needed/demanded in order to (understand/make real/achieve) the investments needed, 
 with a view to reducing international traffic jams and 
 increasing interconnections. 
 5.3. Communications technology for the poor 
 The GB's style of managing mobile phones in 
 villages can improve the technology's broad-based, 
 pro-poor (direction of pointing/way of thinking/information meeting). In Bangladesh, the (compared to other things) 
 rich sections of villages have usually/(in the past) 
 owned, managed and led the introduction of modern 
 technologies (e.g. crop-watering/rinsing with water). Such patterns of ownership have (claimed to be) resulted in unfair distributions of income and wealth. The fact that (compared to other things) 
 poor people can also own and access modern information technology may go a long way towards 
 reducing poorness and restoring a more fair 
 distribution. 
 The strong institutional abilities (to hold or do something) of poor peoples' 
 organisations, such as micro-finance associations, can 
 help efforts to make the poor the managers of 
 new technologies. This may be carefully thought about/believed an added pay-off on earlier investments in the (creation and construction/ group of objects) 
 of such (away from cities) organisations. Many such organisations 
 in other parts of poor countries could also function as hosts for (related to sending and receiving phone calls, texts, etc.) services and so 
 quickly broaden access by the poor. In this big picture, 
 too, development policy, and not just the market, has 
 an important part to play. 
 
